---
import ServiceLayout from '../layouts/ServiceLayout.astro';
import heroImage from '../assets/images/wp-import/burgess-exam.jpg';
---

<ServiceLayout
  heroImage={heroImage}
  title="Emergency & Urgent Veterinary Care in Lake in the Hills, IL | Healthy Paws Animal Hospital"
  description="Same-day urgent veterinary care in Lake in the Hills, IL during business hours. Acute illness, injuries, and emergencies. Call (815) 322-5400 immediately."
  serviceName="Emergency & Urgent Care"
  serviceDescription="Same-day urgent veterinary care for acute illness and injuries during business hours, with triage and stabilization services."
  faqs={[
    {
      question: 'Does Healthy Paws offer after-hours emergency care?',
      answer: 'We provide urgent and emergency care during our regular business hours (Monday–Wednesday and Friday 7:30 AM–5:00 PM, Thursday 7:30 AM–7:00 PM). We are closed on weekends. For after-hours emergencies, we will direct you to the nearest 24-hour emergency veterinary hospital. Always call us first — our voicemail provides current emergency referral information.',
    },
    {
      question: 'How do I know if my pet needs emergency care?',
      answer: 'Signs that require immediate attention include difficulty breathing, uncontrolled bleeding, inability to urinate, seizures, collapse, suspected poisoning, severe vomiting or diarrhea (especially with blood), trauma from being hit by a car, and sudden inability to walk. When in doubt, call us — we would always rather hear from you and help you decide than have you wait when your pet needs care.',
    },
    {
      question: 'Should I call before bringing my pet in for urgent care?',
      answer: 'Yes, please call (815) 322-5400 before heading to our office. Calling ahead allows our team to prepare for your pet\'s arrival, provide first-aid guidance over the phone, and ensure we can accommodate your pet as quickly as possible. In a true life-threatening emergency, call while you\'re on your way.',
    },
    {
      question: 'What should I bring when I come in for an emergency visit?',
      answer: 'If possible, bring any medications your pet is currently taking, information about what happened (including when symptoms started), and any substances your pet may have ingested. If your pet has a regular vet file elsewhere, knowing that history is helpful but not required — we will never delay care while waiting for records.',
    },
  ]}
  relatedServices={['surgery', 'laboratory-diagnostics', 'pain-management']}
>
  <h2>When Your Pet Needs Urgent Attention</h2>
  <p>
    When your pet is sick or injured and can't wait for a scheduled appointment, our team is here to help. Healthy Paws Animal Hospital provides same-day urgent care during business hours for pets experiencing acute illness, injuries, and other time-sensitive health concerns. <strong>If your pet is having an emergency, call us immediately at (815) 322-5400.</strong>
  </p>
  <p>
    Our team will triage your pet's situation over the phone, provide immediate guidance, and prepare for your arrival so we can begin assessment and treatment as quickly as possible.
  </p>

  <h2>What Constitutes a Veterinary Emergency?</h2>
  <p>
    Some situations require immediate veterinary attention. Bring your pet in right away or call us if you observe any of the following:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Breathing difficulty</strong> — labored breathing, choking, or blue-tinged gums</li>
    <li><strong>Trauma</strong> — hit by car, falls from height, or animal attacks</li>
    <li><strong>Uncontrolled bleeding</strong> — wounds that won't stop bleeding with direct pressure</li>
    <li><strong>Inability to urinate</strong> — straining to urinate with no output (especially in male cats)</li>
    <li><strong>Seizures</strong> — especially first-time seizures or clusters of seizures</li>
    <li><strong>Suspected poisoning</strong> — ingestion of toxic foods, chemicals, plants, or medications</li>
    <li><strong>Collapse or sudden weakness</strong> — inability to stand or sudden loss of consciousness</li>
    <li><strong>Severe vomiting or diarrhea</strong> — particularly with blood, or in very young or senior pets</li>
    <li><strong>Bloated or distended abdomen</strong> — especially in large-breed dogs with nonproductive retching</li>
    <li><strong>Eye injuries</strong> — sudden swelling, discharge, squinting, or visible trauma to the eye</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What to Do in an Emergency</h2>

  <h3>During Business Hours</h3>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Call us at (815) 322-5400</strong> — Our team will assess the situation and give you guidance while you're on the way.</li>
    <li><strong>Keep your pet calm and safe</strong> — Minimize movement if you suspect a broken bone or spinal injury. Wrap your pet gently in a towel or blanket for transport.</li>
    <li><strong>Do not give any medications</strong> — unless specifically instructed by our team.</li>
    <li><strong>Drive safely</strong> — We're preparing for your arrival, so focus on getting here safely.</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>After Hours</h3>
  <p>
    For emergencies outside our business hours, we recommend contacting the nearest 24-hour emergency veterinary hospital. Our voicemail recording provides current referral information and contact numbers. If you're unsure whether your pet's situation can wait until morning, err on the side of caution and seek emergency care.
  </p>

  <h2>Our Urgent Care Capabilities</h2>
  <p>
    When your pet arrives for urgent or emergency care, our team can provide:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Rapid triage and stabilization</li>
    <li><a href="/laboratory-diagnostics/">In-house laboratory diagnostics</a> for fast results</li>
    <li>Digital radiography</li>
    <li>Fluid therapy and supportive care</li>
    <li><a href="/pain-management/">Pain management</a></li>
    <li>Wound care and bandaging</li>
    <li><a href="/surgery/">Emergency surgery</a> when needed</li>
    <li>Toxin decontamination</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Our <a href="/laboratory-diagnostics/">in-house laboratory</a> allows us to run critical blood tests and get results within minutes — not days. This means faster diagnosis and faster treatment for your pet when time matters most.
  </p>

  <h2>Urgent vs. Emergency: What's the Difference?</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Emergencies</strong> are life-threatening situations that require immediate intervention. <strong>Urgent care</strong> addresses conditions that need same-day attention but may not be immediately life-threatening — things like sudden limping, ear infections causing severe discomfort, eye irritation, persistent vomiting, or acute allergic reactions.
  </p>
  <p>
    If you're unsure which category your pet's situation falls into, call us. We will always help you determine the right level of care and ensure your pet is seen as quickly as their condition requires.
  </p>
</ServiceLayout>
